        <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
            <head>Historical Sketch</head>
            <p>German born Fred Otto Becher (1873-1962) provided bookbinding services in Hartford, Connecticut before taking on a partner, another 
            German by the name of Emil Eitel (b. ca. 1858). The firm, Becher &amp; Eitel, was noted for the high quality of their work. In 1951 Becher
            appeared in an advertisement of the Smyth Manufacturing Company of Bloomfield. Becher was still using a Smyth book sewing machine that dated to 
            1891, the oldest continuously used machine the company could locate.</p><p>In the 1960s, President Robert Thorsell and Vice President Kathy Murawski took over
                operation of the company.
            </p>


        </bioghist>
        <scopecontent encodinganalog="520$a">
            <head>Scope and Content</head>
            <p> Order books, sales records, payroll, scrapbook, correspondence, invoices, advertisements, and photographs of a Hartford, Connecticut bookbindery, founded by Fred Otto Becher. Later partner was Emil Eitel .</p>


        </scopecontent>
